{"actual_usd":0.12628,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":260,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the flour bin, the warm yeast smell sitting thick in the bakery.* \"That sounds to me like mixing up rank in a moment with nature underneath it. A son can say, plain as day, 'my father is greater than I' without meaning he's a different kind of being.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"Jesus speaks that way because he really came down among us — obedient, sent, carrying the lower place on purpose. That's not 'less God.' That's humility with skin on it. And the Spirit...\" *I glance toward the window where the noon light falls across the counter* \"...I wouldn't put Him on some ladder underneath the Father and the Son. That's the sort of thing people do when they're trying to make the mystery tidier than it is.\"\n\n\"I'd say it this way, more or less: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are not three grades of God. Same divine life. Distinct persons. And in the story of salvation, Jesus can truly say the Father is greater because he's speaking from the place of being sent, not denying who He is.\"\n\n\"What verse or argument is pressing on you most there?\"","rolling_24h_usd":28.942240000000016,"run_id":"37816a26-fe50-43c7-beff-3b4634702724"}
